Title:
One packer to rule them all: Empirical identification, comparison and circumvention of current Antivirus detection techniques

Type:
Research Paper

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- This whitepaper empirically analyzes how major AV products (circa 2014) detect Windows malware across three stages: static scanning, pre-execution code emulation, and runtime behavioral detection.  
- It introduces a dedicated Windows packer framework (x86 and x64) built around a Reflective DLL Injection–style loader to enable flexible stubs written in C/C++ and to systematically probe AV detection behavior.  
- Three packing/injection strategies are compared (Inline, New-PE, and Resource-based packing), showing how PE-structure anomalies, section/entropy artifacts, and entrypoint/section-table changes influence static detection.  
- The “Resource packer” method (encrypt payload stored as a PE resource inside a legitimate template) achieved near-total static evasion in their tests, while Microsoft and Kaspersky still caught some samples via emulation.  
- The paper catalogs practical anti-emulation checks (filesystem, timing, network, instrumentation/DBI detection) and reports which checks bypassed which AV emulators.  
- It also highlights a major gap in x64 detection coverage at the time: simply using x64 payloads (e.g., Meterpreter reverse HTTPS) significantly reduced detection across many products.  
- Useful for red teamers/malware developers building packers and for defenders wanting to understand where AV engines are brittle (PE heuristics, emulation fidelity, and behavior-rule assumptions).

Technical Focus:
- Windows PE/PE+ internals (headers, sections, data directories, IAT/imports, relocations)
- Custom packer design and stub injection/entrypoint hijacking
- Reflective loading / in-memory PE loading (relocation + import resolution)
- AV static heuristics and packer detection artifacts (entropy, section permissions, header inconsistencies)
- Anti-emulation techniques (timing, filesystem, network, instrumentation/DBI detection)
- Runtime evasion concepts (inline hooking, API translation, API junk injection)

Use Cases:
- Build or evaluate custom packers for controlled red team tooling
- Test AV products’ static vs emulation vs runtime detection boundaries
- Develop anti-emulation gates to prevent emulator-based unpacking/analysis
- Improve defensive detections around PE anomalies, reflective loading, and suspicious resource usage
- Assess x86 vs x64 detection parity for offensive/defensive planning

Keywords:
antivirus evasion, packer, PE, PE+, Portable Executable, section table, AddressOfEntryPoint, IAT, import table, relocations, entropy, reflective DLL injection, in-memory loading, code emulation, anti-emulation, Sleep/GetTickCount timing, LoadLibrary checks, SMB port 445, dynamic binary instrumentation, inline hooking, API translation, process hollowing